<subSubSection id="8D9386C8944BFFE51AB2FEF5FC36FEB6" pageId="2" pageNumber="259" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="C536D543944BFFE51AB2FEF5FC36FEB6" blockId="2.[151,1437,290,1540]" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">
<emphasis id="F7FD0951944BFFE51AB2FEF5FEC4FEEA" bold="true" box="[151,286,290,316]" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">Etymology.</emphasis>
The generic name combines the prefix “ 
<emphasis id="F7FD0951944BFFE518CCFEF5FCD2FEEA" box="[745,776,290,316]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">bi-</emphasis>
” referring to its bidentate mandibles (with both apical and subapical teeth) and the name 
<taxonomicName id="0289AEC0944BFFE51BCEFE91FDAFFEB6" authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1906" box="[491,629,326,352]" class="Insecta" family="Artematopodidae" genus="Allopogonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="259" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F7FD0951944BFFE51BCEFE91FDAFFEB6" box="[491,629,326,352]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">Allopogonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The name is feminine in gender.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8D9386C8944BFFE51AE2FEBEFA84FE27" pageId="2" pageNumber="259" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="C536D543944BFFE51AE2FEBEFA84FE27" blockId="2.[151,1437,290,1540]" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">
<emphasis id="F7FD0951944BFFE51AE2FEBEFE98FE55" bold="true" box="[199,322,361,387]" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Antennomeres 5–10 distinctly serrate, less than twice as long as wide (
<figureCitation id="5DB2C9C6944BFFE51E41FEBDFB1BFE52" box="[1124,1217,362,388]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1503,1527]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1480]" captionTargetId="figure-22@4.[151,1436,181,1480]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Details of Bipogonia trivialis Li, Kundrata &amp; Cai gen. et sp. nov., holotype, NIGP179428, under confocal microscopy. A, Head, ventral view. B, Prothorax, ventral view. C, Mesothorax, ventral view. D, Mid leg. E, Metathorax and abdominal base, ventral view. F, Elytral and abdominal apices, showing the interlocking tongue (arrowhead). G, Head, dorsal view. H, Pronotum and antenna, dorsal view. I, Elytron, dorsal view.Abbreviations: a1–11, antennomeres 1–11; cl, clypeus; ep, elytral epipleuron; ey, compound eye; md, mandible; mstb, mesotibia; msts, mesotarsus; msv, mesoventrite; mt, mentum; mtc, metacoxa; mttc, metatrochanter; mtv, metaventrite; pn, pronotum; ps, prosternum; ptb, protibia; pts, protarsus; v1–5, ventrites 1–5. Scale bars: 300 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500935" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500935/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">Figs 3H</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="5DB2C9C6944BFFE51EE8FEBDFB34FE52" box="[1229,1262,362,388]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1503,1527]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1480]" captionTargetId="figure-18@7.[151,1436,181,1480]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 7. Details of Bipogonia fortis Li, Kundrata &amp; Cai sp. nov., holotype, NIGP179431, under confocal microscopy. A, Head, ventral view. B, Prothorax, ventral view. C, Mesothorax, ventral view. D, Meso- and metatarsi. E, Elytral apex, showing the interlocking tongue (arrowhead). F, Antenna. G, Head, dorsal view. H, Scutellar shield, dorsal view. I, Abdominal apex, dorsal view. Abbreviations: a1–11, antennomeres 1–11; cl, clypeus; el, elytron; md, mandible; msts, mesotarsus; msv, mesoventrite; mtc, metacoxa; mtts, metatarsus; mtv, metaventrite; mxp, maxillary palp; pn, pronotum; ps, prosternum; pts, protarsus; sc, scutellum; t8, tergite VIII; v5, ventrite 5. Scale bars: 300 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500945" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500945/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">7F</figureCitation>
). Anterior edge of frontoclypeus dentate (
<figureCitation id="5DB2C9C6944BFFE51B90FE59FDCBFE7E" box="[437,529,398,424]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1503,1527]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1480]" captionTargetId="figure-22@4.[151,1436,181,1480]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Details of Bipogonia trivialis Li, Kundrata &amp; Cai gen. et sp. nov., holotype, NIGP179428, under confocal microscopy. A, Head, ventral view. B, Prothorax, ventral view. C, Mesothorax, ventral view. D, Mid leg. E, Metathorax and abdominal base, ventral view. F, Elytral and abdominal apices, showing the interlocking tongue (arrowhead). G, Head, dorsal view. H, Pronotum and antenna, dorsal view. I, Elytron, dorsal view.Abbreviations: a1–11, antennomeres 1–11; cl, clypeus; ep, elytral epipleuron; ey, compound eye; md, mandible; mstb, mesotibia; msts, mesotarsus; msv, mesoventrite; mt, mentum; mtc, metacoxa; mttc, metatrochanter; mtv, metaventrite; pn, pronotum; ps, prosternum; ptb, protibia; pts, protarsus; v1–5, ventrites 1–5. Scale bars: 300 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500935" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500935/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">Figs 3G</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="5DB2C9C6944BFFE51838FE59FD99FE7E" box="[541,579,398,424]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1503,1527]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1480]" captionTargetId="figure-18@7.[151,1436,181,1480]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 7. Details of Bipogonia fortis Li, Kundrata &amp; Cai sp. nov., holotype, NIGP179431, under confocal microscopy. A, Head, ventral view. B, Prothorax, ventral view. C, Mesothorax, ventral view. D, Meso- and metatarsi. E, Elytral apex, showing the interlocking tongue (arrowhead). F, Antenna. G, Head, dorsal view. H, Scutellar shield, dorsal view. I, Abdominal apex, dorsal view. Abbreviations: a1–11, antennomeres 1–11; cl, clypeus; el, elytron; md, mandible; msts, mesotarsus; msv, mesoventrite; mtc, metacoxa; mtts, metatarsus; mtv, metaventrite; mxp, maxillary palp; pn, pronotum; ps, prosternum; pts, protarsus; sc, scutellum; t8, tergite VIII; v5, ventrite 5. Scale bars: 300 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500945" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500945/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">7G</figureCitation>
). Mandibles with subapical tooth (
<figureCitation id="5DB2C9C6944BFFE519E6FE59FBFAFE7E" box="[963,1056,398,424]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1503,1527]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1480]" captionTargetId="figure-22@4.[151,1436,181,1480]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Details of Bipogonia trivialis Li, Kundrata &amp; Cai gen. et sp. nov., holotype, NIGP179428, under confocal microscopy. A, Head, ventral view. B, Prothorax, ventral view. C, Mesothorax, ventral view. D, Mid leg. E, Metathorax and abdominal base, ventral view. F, Elytral and abdominal apices, showing the interlocking tongue (arrowhead). G, Head, dorsal view. H, Pronotum and antenna, dorsal view. I, Elytron, dorsal view.Abbreviations: a1–11, antennomeres 1–11; cl, clypeus; ep, elytral epipleuron; ey, compound eye; md, mandible; mstb, mesotibia; msts, mesotarsus; msv, mesoventrite; mt, mentum; mtc, metacoxa; mttc, metatrochanter; mtv, metaventrite; pn, pronotum; ps, prosternum; ptb, protibia; pts, protarsus; v1–5, ventrites 1–5. Scale bars: 300 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500935" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500935/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">Figs 3G</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="5DB2C9C6944BFFE51E0EFE59FB8BFE7E" box="[1067,1105,398,424]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1503,1527]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1480]" captionTargetId="figure-18@7.[151,1436,181,1480]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 7. Details of Bipogonia fortis Li, Kundrata &amp; Cai sp. nov., holotype, NIGP179431, under confocal microscopy. A, Head, ventral view. B, Prothorax, ventral view. C, Mesothorax, ventral view. D, Meso- and metatarsi. E, Elytral apex, showing the interlocking tongue (arrowhead). F, Antenna. G, Head, dorsal view. H, Scutellar shield, dorsal view. I, Abdominal apex, dorsal view. Abbreviations: a1–11, antennomeres 1–11; cl, clypeus; el, elytron; md, mandible; msts, mesotarsus; msv, mesoventrite; mtc, metacoxa; mtts, metatarsus; mtv, metaventrite; mxp, maxillary palp; pn, pronotum; ps, prosternum; pts, protarsus; sc, scutellum; t8, tergite VIII; v5, ventrite 5. Scale bars: 300 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500945" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500945/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">7G</figureCitation>
). Apical maxillary palpomere not clearly expanded apically (
<figureCitation id="5DB2C9C6944BFFE51BD4FE65FD97FE1A" box="[497,589,434,460]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,955,979]" captionTargetBox="[223,1365,181,931]" captionTargetId="figure-18@5.[223,1365,181,931]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Bipogonia trivialis Li, Kundrata &amp; Cai gen. et sp. nov., paratypes. A, B, NIGP179429, under incident light. A, Dorsal view. B, Ventral view. C, D, NIGP179430, under widefield fluorescence. C, Head, dorsal view. D, Elytral apices, dorsal view. Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500939" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500939/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">Figs 4C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="5DB2C9C6944BFFE5187CFE65FDA4FE1A" box="[601,638,434,460]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1503,1527]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1480]" captionTargetId="figure-18@7.[151,1436,181,1480]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 7. Details of Bipogonia fortis Li, Kundrata &amp; Cai sp. nov., holotype, NIGP179431, under confocal microscopy. A, Head, ventral view. B, Prothorax, ventral view. C, Mesothorax, ventral view. D, Meso- and metatarsi. E, Elytral apex, showing the interlocking tongue (arrowhead). F, Antenna. G, Head, dorsal view. H, Scutellar shield, dorsal view. I, Abdominal apex, dorsal view. Abbreviations: a1–11, antennomeres 1–11; cl, clypeus; el, elytron; md, mandible; msts, mesotarsus; msv, mesoventrite; mtc, metacoxa; mtts, metatarsus; mtv, metaventrite; mxp, maxillary palp; pn, pronotum; ps, prosternum; pts, protarsus; sc, scutellum; t8, tergite VIII; v5, ventrite 5. Scale bars: 300 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500945" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500945/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">7A</figureCitation>
). Prosternum in front of coxae without paired longitudinal ridges (
<figureCitation id="5DB2C9C6944BFFE51F4EFE65FF60FE26" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1503,1527]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1480]" captionTargetId="figure-22@4.[151,1436,181,1480]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Details of Bipogonia trivialis Li, Kundrata &amp; Cai gen. et sp. nov., holotype, NIGP179428, under confocal microscopy. A, Head, ventral view. B, Prothorax, ventral view. C, Mesothorax, ventral view. D, Mid leg. E, Metathorax and abdominal base, ventral view. F, Elytral and abdominal apices, showing the interlocking tongue (arrowhead). G, Head, dorsal view. H, Pronotum and antenna, dorsal view. I, Elytron, dorsal view.Abbreviations: a1–11, antennomeres 1–11; cl, clypeus; ep, elytral epipleuron; ey, compound eye; md, mandible; mstb, mesotibia; msts, mesotarsus; msv, mesoventrite; mt, mentum; mtc, metacoxa; mttc, metatrochanter; mtv, metaventrite; pn, pronotum; ps, prosternum; ptb, protibia; pts, protarsus; v1–5, ventrites 1–5. Scale bars: 300 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500935" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500935/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">Figs 3B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="5DB2C9C6944BFFE51AE3FE01FF30FE26" box="[198,234,470,496]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1503,1527]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1480]" captionTargetId="figure-18@7.[151,1436,181,1480]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 7. Details of Bipogonia fortis Li, Kundrata &amp; Cai sp. nov., holotype, NIGP179431, under confocal microscopy. A, Head, ventral view. B, Prothorax, ventral view. C, Mesothorax, ventral view. D, Meso- and metatarsi. E, Elytral apex, showing the interlocking tongue (arrowhead). F, Antenna. G, Head, dorsal view. H, Scutellar shield, dorsal view. I, Abdominal apex, dorsal view. Abbreviations: a1–11, antennomeres 1–11; cl, clypeus; el, elytron; md, mandible; msts, mesotarsus; msv, mesoventrite; mtc, metacoxa; mtts, metatarsus; mtv, metaventrite; mxp, maxillary palp; pn, pronotum; ps, prosternum; pts, protarsus; sc, scutellum; t8, tergite VIII; v5, ventrite 5. Scale bars: 300 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500945" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500945/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">7B</figureCitation>
). Elytra with 10 puncture rows (
<figureCitation id="5DB2C9C6944BFFE51871FE01FD78FE26" box="[596,674,470,496]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1503,1527]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1480]" captionTargetId="figure-22@4.[151,1436,181,1480]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Details of Bipogonia trivialis Li, Kundrata &amp; Cai gen. et sp. nov., holotype, NIGP179428, under confocal microscopy. A, Head, ventral view. B, Prothorax, ventral view. C, Mesothorax, ventral view. D, Mid leg. E, Metathorax and abdominal base, ventral view. F, Elytral and abdominal apices, showing the interlocking tongue (arrowhead). G, Head, dorsal view. H, Pronotum and antenna, dorsal view. I, Elytron, dorsal view.Abbreviations: a1–11, antennomeres 1–11; cl, clypeus; ep, elytral epipleuron; ey, compound eye; md, mandible; mstb, mesotibia; msts, mesotarsus; msv, mesoventrite; mt, mentum; mtc, metacoxa; mttc, metatrochanter; mtv, metaventrite; pn, pronotum; ps, prosternum; ptb, protibia; pts, protarsus; v1–5, ventrites 1–5. Scale bars: 300 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500935" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500935/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">Fig. 3I</figureCitation>
). Inner posterobasal angle of radial cell almost right (
<figureCitation id="5DB2C9C6944BFFE51EDFFE01FA8BFE27" box="[1274,1361,470,497]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1849,1873]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,597,1826]" captionTargetId="figure-198@6.[151,1436,597,1826]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 6. Details of Bipogonia fortis Li, Kundrata &amp; Cai sp. nov., holotype, NIGP179431, under widefield fluorescence. A, Head and prothorax, dorsal view. B, Head and prothorax, ventral view. C, Elytron, dorsal view. D, Posterior body, ventral view. E, Elytron and hind wing, ventral view. F, Abdominal apex, dorsal view. Abbreviations: an, antenna; el, elytron; md, mandible; mtv, metaventrite; mxp, maxillary palp; pn, pronotum; ps, prosternum; R, radial cell; v1–5, ventrites 1–5. Scale bars: 500 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500943" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500943/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">Fig. 6E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8D9386C8944BFFE51AE2FE2EFEBAFB4A" pageId="2" pageNumber="259" type="description">
<paragraph id="C536D543944BFFE51AE2FE2EFB2BFDC2" blockId="2.[151,1437,290,1540]" box="[199,1265,505,532]" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">
<emphasis id="F7FD0951944BFFE51AE2FE2EFE8BFDC5" bold="true" box="[199,337,505,531]" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">Description</emphasis>
. Body moderately broad to broad, 2.1–2.6 times as long as wide, surface punctate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C536D543944BFFE51AE2FDC9FE8DFD1E" blockId="2.[151,1437,290,1540]" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">
Antennal insertions dorsally exposed. Subantennal groove absent. Frontoclypeal suture absent; anterior clypeal margin multidentate. Antennomeres 2–4 simple, moderately slender; antennomere 5 moderately serrate; antennomeres 6–10 strongly serrate, about as long as wide. Mandibles with one apical and one subapical teeth. Maxillary palps 4-segmented; apical palpomere not clearly expanded apically. 
<collectingRegion id="074D1BA1944BFFE51E11FD5DFB49FD72" box="[1076,1171,650,676]" country="Myanmar" name="Chin" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">Mentum</collectingRegion>
subtriangular, apically broadly rounded.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C536D543944BFFE51AE2FD05FAFAFCE2" blockId="2.[151,1437,290,1540]" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">Pronotal disc subtrapezoidal, widest at base; anterior margin weakly trisinuate; anterior angles somewhat produced; surface without transverse groove. Prosternum in front coxae transverse, without paired ridges or deep pits. Prosternal process with subparallel sides, apically broadly rounded, fitting into mesoventral cavity.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C536D543944BFFE51AE2FCE9FD3FFC3E" blockId="2.[151,1437,290,1540]" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">Scutellar shield widely pentagonal. Elytra elongate; surface with puncture rows; epipleura developed only in anterior third. Mesoventrite short, anteriorly with well-developed mesoventral cavity. Mesocoxal cavities separated by about twice or more the shortest diameter of coxal cavity. Metaventrite more than half as long as wide, with sides widest posteriorly. Metacoxae strongly transverse, almost contiguous, extending laterally to epipleura; metacoxal plate weakly developed but complete to lateral edge.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C536D543944BFFE51AE2FC25FACAFBE6" blockId="2.[151,1437,290,1540]" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">Legs slender; tibiae slightly longer than respective femora, with two tibial spurs; tarsomeres 1 and 5 elongate; tarsomeres 3 and 4 with well-developed, bilobed membranous ventral process. Pretarsal claws simple.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C536D543944BFFE51AE2FBEDFEBAFB4A" blockId="2.[151,1437,290,1540]" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">Abdominal ventrites with margins denticulate. Sutures between all ventrites complete and distinct; suture between ventrites 4 and 5 only weakly curved. Ventrites 1–4 subequal in length; ventrite 5 about 1.6–1.7 times as long as ventrite 4.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8D9386C8944BFFE51AE2FB71FAE4F9D2" pageId="2" pageNumber="259" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="C536D543944BFFE51AE2FB71FAE4F9D2" blockId="2.[151,1437,290,1540]" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">
<emphasis id="F7FD0951944BFFE51AE2FB71FEE1FB16" bold="true" box="[199,315,1190,1216]" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">Remarks.</emphasis>
Among previously reported genera of 
<taxonomicName id="0289AEC0944BFFE5192DFB71FC17FB16" authorityName="Lacordaire" authorityYear="1857" box="[776,973,1190,1216]" class="Insecta" family="Artematopodidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="259" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Artematopodidae</taxonomicName>
, only 
<taxonomicName id="0289AEC0944BFFE51E3FFB71FB7EFB16" authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1906" box="[1050,1188,1190,1216]" class="Insecta" family="Artematopodidae" genus="Allopogonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="259" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F7FD0951944BFFE51E3FFB71FB7EFB16" box="[1050,1188,1190,1216]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">Allopogonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known to possess strongly serrate antennae and prosternum without paired ridges (
<bibRefCitation id="A118A8B2944BFFE5194CFB1DFBC1FB33" author="Lawrence, J. F." box="[873,1051,1226,1253]" pageId="2" pageNumber="259" pagination="223 - 236" refId="ref5779" refString="Lawrence, J. F. (2005) Brevipogon, a new genus of North American Artematopodidae (Coleoptera). The Coleopterists Bulletin, 59, 223 - 236. https: // doi. org / 10.1649 / 749" type="journal article" year="2005">Lawrence 2005</bibRefCitation>
; 
<figureCitation id="5DB2C9C6944BFFE51E02FB1DFB77FB32" box="[1063,1197,1226,1252]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1870,1894]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,309,1846]" captionTargetId="figure-81@12.[151,1436,309,1846]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 11. Details of extant Allopogonia villosa (Horn), NHMUK010189601, dissection prepared by R. A. Crowson. Photo credit: ©The Trustees of the Natural History Museum, London, licensed under CC BY 4.0. A, Head. B, Prothorax. C, D, Fore legs. E, Mesothorax. F, Elytron. G, Metathorax. H, Abdomen. I, J, Hind wings. K, Hind leg. L, Mandible. M, Labium. N, Maxilla.Abbreviations: msf, mesofemur; mstb, mesotibia; mtf, metafemur; mttb, metatibia; mtv, metaventrite; pf, profemur; ps, prosternum; ptb, protibia; pts, protarsus; v2–5, ventrites 2–5. Scale bars: 500 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500954" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500954/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">Fig. 11A, B</figureCitation>
). In other genera, the antennae are more filiform (if slightly serrate, antennomere more than twice as long as wide), and there is a pair of longitudinal ridges on the prosternum in front of coxae continuous with the lateral margins of prosternal process. 
<taxonomicName id="0289AEC0944BFFE51AB2FAE0FED6FA86" authority="Li &amp; Kundrata &amp; Huang &amp; Cai, 2022" authorityName="Li &amp; Kundrata &amp; Huang &amp; Cai" authorityYear="2022" box="[151,268,1335,1360]" class="Insecta" family="Artematopodidae" genus="Bipogonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="259" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="F7FD0951944BFFE51AB2FAE0FED6FA86" box="[151,268,1335,1360]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">Bipogonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="F7FD0951944BFFE51B30FAE1FE5BFA86" bold="true" box="[277,385,1334,1360]" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="ECCEB42A944BFFE51B30FAE1FE5BFA86" box="[277,385,1334,1360]" pageId="2" pageNumber="259" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="0289AEC0944BFFE51839FAE1FD7CFA86" authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1906" box="[540,678,1334,1360]" class="Insecta" family="Artematopodidae" genus="Allopogonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="259" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F7FD0951944BFFE51839FAE1FD7CFA86" box="[540,678,1334,1360]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">Allopogonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having strongly serrate antennae and lacking prosternal ridges. 
<taxonomicName id="0289AEC0944BFFE51AB2FA8DFEFBFAA2" authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1906" box="[151,289,1370,1396]" class="Insecta" family="Artematopodidae" genus="Allopogonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="259" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F7FD0951944BFFE51AB2FA8DFEFBFAA2" box="[151,289,1370,1396]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">Allopogonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, however, differs from 
<taxonomicName id="0289AEC0944BFFE5180DFA8CFD47FAA2" authorityName="Li &amp; Kundrata &amp; Huang &amp; Cai" authorityYear="2022" box="[552,669,1371,1396]" class="Insecta" family="Artematopodidae" genus="Bipogonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="259" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F7FD0951944BFFE5180DFA8CFD47FAA2" box="[552,669,1371,1396]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">Bipogonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in mandibles without a subapical tooth (
<figureCitation id="5DB2C9C6944BFFE51E47FA8DFB1EFAA2" box="[1122,1220,1370,1396]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1870,1894]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,309,1846]" captionTargetId="figure-81@12.[151,1436,309,1846]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 11. Details of extant Allopogonia villosa (Horn), NHMUK010189601, dissection prepared by R. A. Crowson. Photo credit: ©The Trustees of the Natural History Museum, London, licensed under CC BY 4.0. A, Head. B, Prothorax. C, D, Fore legs. E, Mesothorax. F, Elytron. G, Metathorax. H, Abdomen. I, J, Hind wings. K, Hind leg. L, Mandible. M, Labium. N, Maxilla.Abbreviations: msf, mesofemur; mstb, mesotibia; mtf, metafemur; mttb, metatibia; mtv, metaventrite; pf, profemur; ps, prosternum; ptb, protibia; pts, protarsus; v2–5, ventrites 2–5. Scale bars: 500 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6500954" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6500954/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">Fig. 11L</figureCitation>
), which is a unique character state in 
<taxonomicName id="0289AEC0944BFFE51B41FAA9FD2DFA4F" authority="(Lawrence 2005)" baseAuthorityName="Lawrence" baseAuthorityYear="2005" box="[356,759,1406,1433]" class="Insecta" family="Artematopodidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="259" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">
Artematopodidae (
<bibRefCitation id="A118A8B2944BFFE5181DFAA9FD35FA4F" author="Lawrence, J. F." box="[568,751,1406,1433]" pageId="2" pageNumber="259" pagination="223 - 236" refId="ref5779" refString="Lawrence, J. F. (2005) Brevipogon, a new genus of North American Artematopodidae (Coleoptera). The Coleopterists Bulletin, 59, 223 - 236. https: // doi. org / 10.1649 / 749" type="journal article" year="2005">Lawrence 2005</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName id="0289AEC0944BFFE51921FAA8FCA3FA4E" authorityName="Li &amp; Kundrata &amp; Huang &amp; Cai" authorityYear="2022" box="[772,889,1407,1432]" class="Insecta" family="Artematopodidae" genus="Bipogonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="259" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F7FD0951944BFFE51921FAA8FCA3FA4E" box="[772,889,1407,1432]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">Bipogonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the anterior edge of frontoclypeus dentate, while in most other artematopodids the anterior clypeal margin is rounded. Extant artematopodids have 11 or 12 puncture rows on each elytron (
<bibRefCitation id="A118A8B2944BFFE51BD3FA11FD72FA37" author="Lawrence, J. F." box="[502,680,1478,1505]" pageId="2" pageNumber="259" pagination="223 - 236" refId="ref5779" refString="Lawrence, J. F. (2005) Brevipogon, a new genus of North American Artematopodidae (Coleoptera). The Coleopterists Bulletin, 59, 223 - 236. https: // doi. org / 10.1649 / 749" type="journal article" year="2005">Lawrence 2005</bibRefCitation>
; fig. 3G in 
<bibRefCitation id="A118A8B2944BFFE51901FA11FC2BFA36" author="Wang, C. - B. &amp; Liu, H. - Y." box="[804,1009,1478,1504]" pageId="2" pageNumber="259" pagination="37 - 42" refId="ref6629" refString="Wang, C. - B. &amp; Liu, H. - Y. (2021) Eurypogon sanzang sp. n. from Henan, China (Coleoptera: Artematopodidae: Artematopodinae). Japanese Journal of Systematic Entomology, 27, 37 - 42." type="journal article" year="2021">Wang &amp; Liu 2021</bibRefCitation>
). However, there are probably only 10 elytral puncture rows in 
<taxonomicName id="0289AEC0944BFFE51B8CFA3CFDC4F9D2" authority="Li &amp; Kundrata &amp; Huang &amp; Cai, 2022" authorityName="Li &amp; Kundrata &amp; Huang &amp; Cai" authorityYear="2022" box="[425,542,1515,1540]" class="Insecta" family="Artematopodidae" genus="Bipogonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="259" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="F7FD0951944BFFE51B8CFA3CFDC4F9D2" box="[425,542,1515,1540]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">Bipogonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="F7FD0951944BFFE51800FA3DFD54F9D2" bold="true" box="[549,654,1514,1540]" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="ECCEB42A944BFFE51800FA3DFD54F9D2" box="[549,654,1514,1540]" pageId="2" pageNumber="259" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(as seen in 
<taxonomicName id="0289AEC0944BFFE51937FA3CFC52F9D2" authorityName="Li &amp; Kundrata &amp; Huang &amp; Cai" authorityYear="2022" box="[786,904,1514,1540]" class="Insecta" family="Artematopodidae" genus="Bipogonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="259" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trivialis">
<emphasis id="F7FD0951944BFFE51937FA3CFC52F9D2" box="[786,904,1514,1540]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">B. trivialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), as well as 
<taxonomicName id="0289AEC0944BFFE51E36FA3DFB14F9D2" authority="Li &amp; Kundrata &amp; Huang &amp; Cai, 2022" authorityName="Li &amp; Kundrata &amp; Huang &amp; Cai" authorityYear="2022" box="[1043,1230,1514,1540]" class="Insecta" family="Artematopodidae" genus="Carinibipogonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="259" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="F7FD0951944BFFE51E36FA3DFB14F9D2" box="[1043,1230,1514,1540]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">Carinibipogonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="F7FD0951944BFFE51EF0FA3DFAE4F9D2" bold="true" box="[1237,1342,1514,1540]" pageId="2" pageNumber="259">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="ECCEB42A944BFFE51EF0FA3DFAE4F9D2" box="[1237,1342,1514,1540]" pageId="2" pageNumber="259" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
